00:43:21.360 --> 00:43:24.900
Let us now briefly review the

00:43:24.900 --> 00:43:28.200
history of the discipline of

00:43:28.200 --> 00:43:29.400
organizational behavior.

00:43:31.320 --> 00:43:33.400
Surprisingly enough,

00:43:33.780 --> 00:43:35.580
organizational behavior has

00:43:35.580 --> 00:43:38.720
a history of over 100 years.

00:43:39.900 --> 00:43:41.980
The first studies of organizational behavior,

00:43:42.140 --> 00:43:43.920
not yet naturally so named, began

00:43:43.920 --> 00:43:48.420
in the late nineteenth and early twentieth

00:43:48.420 --> 00:43:49.900
centuries.

00:43:51.180 --> 00:43:53.040
This was largely due to the

00:43:53.040 --> 00:43:57.400
fact that there was industrial

00:43:57.400 --> 00:44:02.200
growth, new factories, plants,

00:44:02.200 --> 00:44:05.800
a stage of industrial development,

00:44:05.800 --> 00:44:07.340
the end of the nineteenth

00:44:07.340 --> 00:44:08.600
century.

00:44:09.740 --> 00:44:11.540
And, accordingly, a great

00:44:11.540 --> 00:44:13.620
number of people were included

00:44:13.620 --> 00:44:16.420
in this industrial production.

00:44:17.600 --> 00:44:21.620
Of course, at that time,

00:44:21.620 --> 00:44:24.480
a person's job was to stand

00:44:24.480 --> 00:44:27.640
at a machine, or you stood

00:44:27.640 --> 00:44:29.140
at some other mechanism,

00:44:29.140 --> 00:44:31.040
and your task was

00:44:31.040 --> 00:44:32.620
to reproduce these

00:44:32.620 --> 00:44:35.560
or those actions,

00:44:35.560 --> 00:44:37.600
to make the mechanism

00:44:37.600 --> 00:44:39.440
work.

00:44:40.000 --> 00:44:42.260
The fact that the end of the XIX century,

00:44:42.260 --> 00:44:43.560
and in general the formation of industrial

00:44:43.560 --> 00:44:45.500
production was largely associated

00:44:45.500 --> 00:44:48.320
with advances in technology, mechanics.

00:44:48.640 --> 00:44:50.760
New machines, new devices, new

00:44:50.760 --> 00:44:53.840
machines were created, which

00:44:53.840 --> 00:44:56.920
were connected both with the

00:44:56.920 --> 00:44:58.880
gasoline engine, and with

00:44:58.880 --> 00:44:59.680
the internal combustion

00:44:59.680 --> 00:45:00.920
engine, as they developed

00:45:00.920 --> 00:45:03.880
further, and in this situation,

00:45:03.880 --> 00:45:06.800
man was regarded as a principal

00:45:06.800 --> 00:45:09.100
adjunct to this mechanism.

00:45:09.100 --> 00:45:09.820


00:45:10.140 --> 00:45:11.860
Here is a very important approach.

00:45:12.760 --> 00:45:14.140
In principle, it was with this

00:45:14.140 --> 00:45:15.620
approach, or rather, not agreeing with

00:45:15.620 --> 00:45:18.040
it, that the analysis of

00:45:18.040 --> 00:45:19.160
organizational behavior began.

00:45:19.720 --> 00:45:23.040
The end of the 19th century, the industrial

00:45:23.040 --> 00:45:26.700
revolution, the development of those either on

00:45:26.700 --> 00:45:29.460
their production, but the factories, and the main

00:45:29.460 --> 00:45:31.320
influence, the main importance in them was

00:45:31.320 --> 00:45:33.340
given precisely to devices, precisely to mechanisms,

00:45:33.340 --> 00:45:35.120
precisely to machinery.

00:45:35.820 --> 00:45:39.100
Man was not simply a service

00:45:39.100 --> 00:45:41.060
mechanism; he was seen

00:45:41.060 --> 00:45:42.620
as the same part of technology.

00:45:42.620 --> 00:45:43.300


00:45:43.420 --> 00:45:45.440
And if machinery was

00:45:45.440 --> 00:45:48.920
reliable, well-equipped,

00:45:48.920 --> 00:45:51.080
invested in, then man was

00:45:51.080 --> 00:45:53.920
the weakest part of

00:45:53.920 --> 00:45:56.140
technical progress.

00:45:56.600 --> 00:46:00.080
He got tired, he made mistakes, he

00:46:00.080 --> 00:46:01.980
had to be interrupted, he had

00:46:01.980 --> 00:46:05.360
to be fed, he had to be trained.

00:46:05.680 --> 00:46:06.920
After all, that man could break

00:46:06.920 --> 00:46:09.420
an expensive machine.

00:46:09.760 --> 00:46:13.280
And if that or our tank cost a

00:46:13.280 --> 00:46:14.460
lot of money and had to be

00:46:14.460 --> 00:46:16.360
bought, the man could always be

00:46:16.360 --> 00:46:17.580
easily replaced.

00:46:18.320 --> 00:46:20.220
If you can't work, then it wasn't

00:46:20.220 --> 00:46:21.480
a question of if you wanted to.

00:46:21.880 --> 00:46:23.900
If you can't work, I'll find

00:46:23.900 --> 00:46:25.240
someone who can work and put

00:46:25.240 --> 00:46:26.360
him on that machine.

00:46:26.800 --> 00:46:29.980
If he makes mistakes, I will

00:46:29.980 --> 00:46:32.380
change him and find someone else

00:46:32.380 --> 00:46:33.860
who makes fewer mistakes, and so on.

00:46:35.080 --> 00:46:37.560
That's the situation that arose.

00:46:38.100 --> 00:46:39.440
In this case it was a question of

00:46:39.520 --> 00:46:41.200
the man being a traitor to the machine.

00:46:41.480 --> 00:46:44.080
And that was the prevailing view of

00:46:44.080 --> 00:46:45.820
the late nineteenth century, early

00:46:46.080 --> 00:46:47.560
twentieth century.

00:46:51.030 --> 00:46:54.730
It is worth mentioning here such

00:46:54.730 --> 00:46:57.030
a man as Frederick Winslot Taylor.

00:46:58.170 --> 00:47:02.930
The thing about Taylor is that he

00:47:02.930 --> 00:47:05.610
was just thinking about this question.

00:47:06.110 --> 00:47:08.670
What is man's place in this

00:47:08.670 --> 00:47:09.850
industrial production?

00:47:10.290 --> 00:47:11.670
Is man really

00:47:11.670 --> 00:47:17.950
just a certain trait

00:47:17.950 --> 00:47:20.850
to operate the machine.

00:47:22.770 --> 00:47:25.410
Taylor began to investigate the behavior

00:47:25.410 --> 00:47:28.190
of the workers, at the time he had

00:47:28.190 --> 00:47:29.650
no problem because no one was asking

00:47:29.650 --> 00:47:32.590
for these workers' consent, their wishes,

00:47:32.590 --> 00:47:35.850
and yes, let's just say he wasn't

00:47:35.850 --> 00:47:37.650
really distracting them, he was just

00:47:37.650 --> 00:47:40.110
observing how they worked, when

00:47:40.110 --> 00:47:43.510
they made mistakes, when they

00:47:43.730 --> 00:47:45.410
began to get tired.

00:47:46.630 --> 00:47:49.070
He was the process of working, he was the observer.

00:47:50.310 --> 00:47:52.890
And, accordingly, Taylor drew

00:47:52.890 --> 00:47:56.130
attention to the fact that the

00:47:56.930 --> 00:47:58.830
person working on the machine

00:47:59.290 --> 00:48:00.930
was not such an

00:48:00.930 --> 00:48:03.550
auxiliary element.

00:48:04.470 --> 00:48:06.730
Moreover, he observed that

00:48:06.730 --> 00:48:09.310
the success, the efficiency

00:48:09.310 --> 00:48:11.210
of any particular machine,

00:48:11.210 --> 00:48:14.550
any particular mechanism,

00:48:14.550 --> 00:48:18.590
depends largely on how

00:48:18.590 --> 00:48:22.050
the man works with that machine.

00:48:22.750 --> 00:48:25.110
How he likes to work, how he dislikes

00:48:25.110 --> 00:48:26.010
to work.

00:48:26.510 --> 00:48:29.130
How motivated he is to work with that

00:48:29.130 --> 00:48:29.850
machine.

00:48:31.750 --> 00:48:33.270
In addition, Taylor drew attention

00:48:33.270 --> 00:48:35.290
to another aspect.

00:48:37.570 --> 00:48:40.110
Depending on what kind of

00:48:40.110 --> 00:48:42.470
workload on a person, how much

00:48:42.470 --> 00:48:44.910
time he works, the number

00:48:44.910 --> 00:48:47.010
of errors increases.

00:48:47.890 --> 00:48:51.350
And, accordingly, just by purely

00:48:51.350 --> 00:48:53.510
empirical way he drew attention

00:48:53.510 --> 00:48:55.030
to the fact that if a person works a

00:48:55.030 --> 00:48:57.390
certain amount of time, I'll

00:48:57.390 --> 00:48:59.990
replace him with another person,

00:48:59.990 --> 00:49:01.870
so that the first one has a rest,

00:49:01.870 --> 00:49:06.370
then the number of errors decreases,

00:49:06.370 --> 00:49:09.470
as long as the person has

00:49:09.470 --> 00:49:12.170
an opportunity to rest.

00:49:12.370 --> 00:49:14.110
The person, as they call it, takes a breather.

00:49:14.410 --> 00:49:15.530
And after he goes

00:49:15.530 --> 00:49:19.050
back to work on his machine,

00:49:19.050 --> 00:49:22.190
his mechanism,

00:49:23.230 --> 00:49:25.230
his productivity increases.

00:49:25.710 --> 00:49:27.250
And then Taylor simply began

00:49:27.250 --> 00:49:28.810
to make all sorts of experiments,

00:49:31.150 --> 00:49:33.010
in order to grasp how much

00:49:33.010 --> 00:49:36.870
time it is desirable for a

00:49:36.870 --> 00:49:39.590
man to work in order not

00:49:39.710 --> 00:49:42.650
to commit all sorts of mistakes.

00:49:44.490 --> 00:49:46.330
Those studies that Taylor conducted,

00:49:46.330 --> 00:49:48.410
and let only he published them,

00:49:48.410 --> 00:49:51.430
got the name, and now widely

00:49:51.430 --> 00:49:52.650
known, as the scientific

00:49:52.650 --> 00:49:54.330
organization of work.

00:49:54.550 --> 00:49:56.030
And with the name of Frederick Taylor is

00:49:56.030 --> 00:49:58.390
precisely the creation of this concept

00:49:58.390 --> 00:50:00.190
of scientific organization of labor.

00:50:00.970 --> 00:50:02.970
This concept has already proceeded

00:50:02.970 --> 00:50:07.630
from the premise that man cannot

00:50:07.630 --> 00:50:10.250
and should not be viewed simply as

00:50:10.250 --> 00:50:11.850
a traitor to some system.

00:50:12.230 --> 00:50:15.330
It is not a traitor, it is a defining

00:50:15.330 --> 00:50:17.410
element, a defining mechanism,

00:50:17.670 --> 00:50:20.170
whose functioning largely

00:50:20.170 --> 00:50:21.650
determines the efficiency,

00:50:21.650 --> 00:50:23.810
the quantitative output that

00:50:23.810 --> 00:50:25.670
results from the work of

00:50:25.670 --> 00:50:27.570
this or that machine.

00:50:30.060 --> 00:50:34.300
Taylor proposed a number of effective

00:50:34.300 --> 00:50:37.800
measures which helped to

00:50:37.800 --> 00:50:40.480
increase labor productivity.

00:50:40.840 --> 00:50:41.920
Naturally, he faced the same

00:50:41.920 --> 00:50:42.740
problem.

00:50:43.240 --> 00:50:45.080
There is a machine, there is

00:50:45.240 --> 00:50:49.180
a man working on that machine, but

00:50:49.180 --> 00:50:50.720
he was interested, and he was not so

00:50:50.720 --> 00:50:51.960
much interested in making the man

00:50:51.960 --> 00:50:54.000
work well, he was interested in a

00:50:54.000 --> 00:50:55.580
pure business problem.

00:50:55.880 --> 00:50:57.660
The machine can produce, roughly

00:50:57.660 --> 00:50:58.660
speaking, 100 parts.

00:50:58.880 --> 00:51:00.780
Because of the fact that there is a man

00:51:00.780 --> 00:51:02.440
working on the machine, who gets tired,

00:51:02.440 --> 00:51:04.900
out of these 100 parts you get 20, 30,

00:51:04.900 --> 00:51:05.580
40 rejects.

00:51:05.920 --> 00:51:06.860
So the machine produces

00:51:06.860 --> 00:51:08.200
60 parts.

00:51:08.920 --> 00:51:11.040
How do you make sure that

00:51:11.040 --> 00:51:13.080
the capacity of the machine, these

00:51:13.080 --> 00:51:14.980
100 parts, they were 100 parts

00:51:14.980 --> 00:51:15.960
in a working day?

00:51:16.300 --> 00:51:20.360
That's the question Taylor was solving,

00:51:20.360 --> 00:51:23.420
and in this connection he came

00:51:23.420 --> 00:51:28.220
to the conclusion, in order for a machine

00:51:28.220 --> 00:51:29.320
tool to work at its full

00:51:29.320 --> 00:51:31.020
efficiency, it is necessary

00:51:31.020 --> 00:51:34.780
to provide a person working on this

00:51:34.780 --> 00:51:36.020
machine with certain working

00:51:36.020 --> 00:51:36.740
conditions.

00:51:38.280 --> 00:51:40.580
It was Taylor the First who introduced

00:51:40.580 --> 00:51:43.080
such a procedure called timekeeping.

00:51:43.500 --> 00:51:46.360
He stood with a stopwatch and measured

00:51:46.760 --> 00:51:49.440
how much time passed, until the

00:51:49.440 --> 00:51:51.420
man began to get tired, how much

00:51:51.420 --> 00:51:52.820
time it took a person to perform

00:51:52.820 --> 00:51:54.780
one operation, another operation,

00:51:55.160 --> 00:51:57.160
a third operation, how easily

00:51:57.660 --> 00:51:59.100
a person could switch

00:51:59.100 --> 00:52:01.460
to perform these or those

00:52:01.460 --> 00:52:02.640
operations.

00:52:03.800 --> 00:52:05.380
And, of course, a person did not work

00:52:05.380 --> 00:52:06.600
alone, because if we take a

00:52:06.600 --> 00:52:08.880
manufactory, there were several machines.

00:52:09.040 --> 00:52:10.500
Each successive one worked on a part

00:52:10.500 --> 00:52:12.060
that had been made by the previous one.

00:52:12.480 --> 00:52:13.680
And here again a situation

00:52:13.680 --> 00:52:16.080
arose which is also very often

00:52:16.080 --> 00:52:17.720
found in modern factories.

00:52:18.260 --> 00:52:21.040
There were very many pieces,

00:52:21.040 --> 00:52:25.260
excess of them, which could

00:52:25.720 --> 00:52:27.940
not be processed on other

00:52:27.940 --> 00:52:28.800
machines.

00:52:28.940 --> 00:52:30.360
There were more complicated operations,

00:52:31.280 --> 00:52:34.040
more time was required for machining,

00:52:34.040 --> 00:52:35.980
and, accordingly, the problem

00:52:36.080 --> 00:52:38.200
arose of an overabundance of some

00:52:38.200 --> 00:52:42.440
parts and a shortage of other parts.

00:52:42.440 --> 00:52:45.700
As a result, the production schedule was

00:52:45.700 --> 00:52:49.320
not followed, and the machines worked at

00:52:49.320 --> 00:52:50.740
odds with each other.

00:52:51.460 --> 00:52:52.900
It was the introduction

00:52:52.900 --> 00:52:55.460
of timing that made it

00:52:55.460 --> 00:52:57.780
possible to synchronize

00:52:57.780 --> 00:53:00.700
production of one

00:53:00.700 --> 00:53:02.640
part or another.

00:53:03.000 --> 00:53:04.620
After all, it was possible to take

00:53:04.620 --> 00:53:09.100
different numbers of machines so that

00:53:09.100 --> 00:53:11.200
all parts were in continuous production.

00:53:11.200 --> 00:53:16.900
There was no assembly line yet, but it

00:53:16.900 --> 00:53:18.560
was thanks to Taylor that timekeeping,

00:53:18.560 --> 00:53:20.740
the timing of working hours,

00:53:20.780 --> 00:53:22.380
was first spoken of.

00:53:23.520 --> 00:53:25.620
In fact, it was this timekeeping

00:53:25.620 --> 00:53:28.300
that was the precursor to later

00:53:28.300 --> 00:53:29.700
assembly-line production.

00:53:31.000 --> 00:53:32.320
But, of course, Taylor did

00:53:32.320 --> 00:53:35.660
not limit himself to timekeeping.

00:53:36.080 --> 00:53:38.620
This is his idea of timekeeping, which,

00:53:38.620 --> 00:53:41.160
among other things, has its development

00:53:41.160 --> 00:53:42.380
today in what are known as

00:53:42.380 --> 00:53:43.920
photographs of working time, photographs

00:53:44.660 --> 00:53:46.380
of the workplace.

00:53:46.820 --> 00:53:49.980
When it is written down by the time

00:53:49.980 --> 00:53:52.700
stage of the employee's performance

00:53:52.700 --> 00:53:54.680
of this or that activity during his

00:53:54.680 --> 00:53:57.300
working day, during those or other

00:53:57.300 --> 00:53:59.380
tasks that he is solving,

00:53:59.380 --> 00:54:01.360
all this comes from Taylor.

00:54:01.440 --> 00:54:04.120
But the same Taylor drew attention

00:54:04.120 --> 00:54:05.000
to another aspect.

00:54:06.220 --> 00:54:10.360
In order for a worker to work effectively

00:54:10.360 --> 00:54:12.220
on this or that machine, he

00:54:12.540 --> 00:54:14.640
must understand what to do.

00:54:14.920 --> 00:54:17.080
That is, roughly speaking, which button

00:54:17.080 --> 00:54:20.200
to push, when to push it,

00:54:20.300 --> 00:54:22.180
and, accordingly, how hard to push it.

00:54:22.940 --> 00:54:24.680
It was Taylor who drew attention

00:54:24.680 --> 00:54:26.740
to the fact that, in fact.

00:54:27.380 --> 00:54:29.560
It is precisely because the worker

00:54:29.560 --> 00:54:32.420
does not quite understand the technique

00:54:32.420 --> 00:54:34.900
of the machine mechanism, the machine control,

00:54:35.480 --> 00:54:37.480
that a large number of defects occur.

00:54:37.800 --> 00:54:39.460
What is experience according to Taylor?

00:54:39.700 --> 00:54:41.660
According to Taylor, experience is that

00:54:41.820 --> 00:54:44.240
an experienced worker already knows

00:54:44.840 --> 00:54:47.060
where to stand, which side to stand on,

00:54:47.180 --> 00:54:49.100
how to hold the part, and

00:54:49.180 --> 00:54:50.060
therefore he will not commit

00:54:50.060 --> 00:54:51.400
a huge number of defects.

00:54:51.480 --> 00:54:55.580
As a result, Taylor initiated

00:54:55.580 --> 00:54:57.380
the creation of so-

00:54:57.380 --> 00:54:59.640
called instruction cards.

00:55:00.040 --> 00:55:02.440
Cards that had written instructions,

00:55:02.440 --> 00:55:04.820
step by step, step-by-step instructions

00:55:04.820 --> 00:55:07.600
of what to do, how, when,

00:55:07.600 --> 00:55:09.300
and in what order.

00:55:10.400 --> 00:55:13.960
And, accordingly, when a new worker

00:55:13.960 --> 00:55:16.180
came to work on this or that

00:55:16.180 --> 00:55:18.120
machine, he would study

00:55:18.120 --> 00:55:20.360
those instructions beforehand.

00:55:20.980 --> 00:55:22.220
Again, today we know very well,

00:55:22.220 --> 00:55:24.380
and it persists.

00:55:24.740 --> 00:55:26.340
It's essentially a safety technique.

00:55:26.960 --> 00:55:28.820
Just as now we sign for safety

00:55:28.820 --> 00:55:29.860
procedures, though we sign without

00:55:29.940 --> 00:55:32.220
reading them, so back then

00:55:32.220 --> 00:55:34.400
the worker studied the

00:55:34.400 --> 00:55:35.560
instruction card.

00:55:36.700 --> 00:55:40.200
And if now, after you studied it,

00:55:40.200 --> 00:55:42.740
after you asked all the questions,

00:55:42.840 --> 00:55:45.180
after you understood what to do,

00:55:45.180 --> 00:55:48.100
you did the defect, then it was your

00:55:48.100 --> 00:55:49.620
own fault, and, accordingly,

00:55:49.620 --> 00:55:51.600
you were fined and sanctioned.

00:55:51.800 --> 00:55:53.460
And you yourself understood that

00:55:53.460 --> 00:55:54.700
it was really your fault, because you

00:55:54.820 --> 00:55:56.920
didn't comply with something, you did

00:55:57.020 --> 00:55:58.860
something in the wrong way, or in some other way.

00:55:59.580 --> 00:56:01.060
So the instructional cards that

00:56:01.100 --> 00:56:02.780
Taylor introduced, they, again,

00:56:02.780 --> 00:56:05.000
still have this or that existence today.

00:56:05.500 --> 00:56:08.200
And not without reason, when you buy

00:56:08.200 --> 00:56:10.060
any complex device, a computer, a camera,

00:56:10.140 --> 00:56:11.740
a video camera, to Taylor, he always

00:56:11.740 --> 00:56:16.340
has an instruction card for the activity.

00:56:16.640 --> 00:56:18.280
This, again, is something that goes back to

00:56:18.280 --> 00:56:21.220
Taylor by the late 19th century.

00:56:22.880 --> 00:56:24.640
The same Taylor drew attention

00:56:24.640 --> 00:56:25.980
to the following fact.

00:56:27.680 --> 00:56:30.020
Machines are different,

00:56:30.020 --> 00:56:35.180
and naturally, when a worker

00:56:35.180 --> 00:56:36.960
works on the same machine, eventually

00:56:37.020 --> 00:56:39.580
he gets bored with that machine.

00:56:39.980 --> 00:56:41.960
It is because man is not

00:56:41.960 --> 00:56:44.180
a machine that the same

00:56:44.180 --> 00:56:45.600
Taylor pointed out.

00:56:46.300 --> 00:56:49.900
The fact is that man constantly wants

00:56:49.900 --> 00:56:51.740
some kind of novelty.

00:56:52.480 --> 00:56:54.900
And so, if you learned to work

00:56:54.900 --> 00:56:56.660
well on one machine, the factory

00:56:56.660 --> 00:56:59.020
owners used to leave you

00:56:59.020 --> 00:57:00.080
on that machine.

00:57:00.160 --> 00:57:01.680
Why would he take someone else, you're already

00:57:01.760 --> 00:57:03.100
successfully working on that machine,

00:57:03.100 --> 00:57:05.060
you already know what to do and how

00:57:05.060 --> 00:57:05.440
to do it.

00:57:05.660 --> 00:57:07.220
But Taylor pointed out that if

00:57:07.220 --> 00:57:09.560
you work very long hours, you lose

00:57:09.640 --> 00:57:11.080
interest in working on that

00:57:11.080 --> 00:57:11.600
machine.

00:57:11.780 --> 00:57:13.920
Your attention dulls, and you start

00:57:13.920 --> 00:57:16.180
getting defective again.

00:57:16.780 --> 00:57:18.740
That's such a protoxic situation.

00:57:19.040 --> 00:57:20.060
If you don't know how to do it, understandably,

00:57:20.060 --> 00:57:21.580
you're learning, so it's a marriage,

00:57:21.700 --> 00:57:23.240
but you already know everything,

00:57:23.240 --> 00:57:24.680
you do everything with your

00:57:24.680 --> 00:57:25.940
eyes closed, and you still get

00:57:25.940 --> 00:57:27.380
a marriage.

00:57:27.660 --> 00:57:31.520
And it was Traylor who formulated

00:57:31.520 --> 00:57:35.280
the problem as worker retraining.

00:57:35.340 --> 00:57:40.840
And, of course, back then psychology

00:57:40.840 --> 00:57:42.580
wasn't as developed and there weren't

00:57:42.580 --> 00:57:44.680
the terms that there are now.

00:57:45.000 --> 00:57:48.680
And, of course, Taylor wasn't

00:57:48.680 --> 00:57:50.620
talking about any career development,

00:57:50.620 --> 00:57:52.580
but the idea was simple, and the

00:57:52.580 --> 00:57:54.700
idea was the same as building

00:57:54.700 --> 00:57:56.260
a modern career tree.

00:57:57.260 --> 00:57:59.760
You've successfully learned to work

00:58:01.940 --> 00:58:03.620
on one machine, but you

00:58:03.880 --> 00:58:06.880
AND naturally want to develop further.

00:58:07.380 --> 00:58:08.920
If only because working on

00:58:08.920 --> 00:58:10.800
another machine pays more.

00:58:11.520 --> 00:58:13.940
If only a material incentive.

00:58:14.300 --> 00:58:16.400
Taylor had only material incentives.

00:58:16.760 --> 00:58:18.240
Taylor did not offer non-material

00:58:18.240 --> 00:58:22.640
incentives at that time.

00:58:22.900 --> 00:58:24.560
Although, a little later on, the

00:58:24.680 --> 00:58:25.640
rudiments of non-material

00:58:25.640 --> 00:58:27.720
incentives were also suggested by Taylor.

00:58:28.520 --> 00:58:30.200
Correspondingly, you want to move

00:58:30.200 --> 00:58:31.680
to another machine, you will have

00:58:31.680 --> 00:58:33.500
renewed interest, you will have

00:58:33.500 --> 00:58:34.560
renewed concentration.

00:58:36.380 --> 00:58:39.320
And so the same retraining

00:58:39.320 --> 00:58:41.100
that you do, it can be successful

00:58:41.440 --> 00:58:43.740
because it will be

00:58:44.040 --> 00:58:45.400
an incentive to your

00:58:45.400 --> 00:58:46.220
work.

00:58:46.700 --> 00:58:49.000
Once you've mastered one machine, you

00:58:49.000 --> 00:58:50.440
can move on to the next machine.

00:58:52.220 --> 00:58:56.780
And if a worker knew that he had

00:58:56.860 --> 00:58:58.200
a job prospect, that if a

00:58:58.200 --> 00:59:02.380
machine was replaced, it didn't

00:59:02.480 --> 00:59:03.800
mean that you'd be out the factory

00:59:03.800 --> 00:59:06.300
gates and you'd be mastering

00:59:06.300 --> 00:59:07.180
another machine.

00:59:07.460 --> 00:59:09.500
It was in his best interest, and his

00:59:09.500 --> 00:59:11.080
motivation to work increased.

00:59:11.180 --> 00:59:13.060
When Taylor proposed the idea

00:59:13.060 --> 00:59:14.240
of retraining, it was not

00:59:14.240 --> 00:59:15.540
received with enthusiasm,

00:59:15.540 --> 00:59:17.280
naturally, because retraining

00:59:17.280 --> 00:59:19.200
is, again, an investment.

00:59:19.480 --> 00:59:23.660
But then it turned out, and the

00:59:23.660 --> 00:59:25.840
factory owners, the shipyard

00:59:25.840 --> 00:59:29.000
owners saw this, that this change

00:59:29.000 --> 00:59:32.540
in attitude to the workers, it would

00:59:32.540 --> 00:59:35.260
be very effective in maximizing

00:59:35.260 --> 00:59:37.400
the efficiency of the equipment

00:59:37.400 --> 00:59:38.920
with which they worked.

00:59:39.900 --> 00:59:41.380
Taylor drew attention again to the

00:59:41.380 --> 00:59:44.360
next step, that when the work

00:59:44.360 --> 00:59:46.740
takes place in this factory, in the

00:59:46.860 --> 00:59:49.240
manufactory, then another very

00:59:49.240 --> 00:59:51.840
important structural element

00:59:51.840 --> 00:59:53.740
has to be included, the planning

00:59:53.880 --> 00:59:54.580
bureau.

00:59:55.580 --> 00:59:58.780
The work shouldn't go like this, you've

00:59:58.780 --> 01:00:00.340
got so many parts, you've got so many

01:00:00.440 --> 01:00:02.780
parts, and then we'll figure it out from there.

01:00:03.340 --> 01:00:05.520
The work must be planned.

01:00:05.800 --> 01:00:07.520
There has to be a plan of how many

01:00:07.520 --> 01:00:09.740
parts, how many blanks to make.

01:00:10.340 --> 01:00:12.280
It must be planned how many of these

01:00:12.280 --> 01:00:14.240
or that kind of part after

01:00:14.240 --> 01:00:17.020
each machine to be able to plan what,

01:00:17.200 --> 01:00:19.060
the amount of work during the working

01:00:20.280 --> 01:00:22.180
day, how many pieces will

01:00:22.180 --> 01:00:24.220
be made, how efficient these

01:00:24.220 --> 01:00:27.040
pieces will be, what the relationship

01:00:27.040 --> 01:00:29.720
should be between the delivery

01:00:29.720 --> 01:00:31.800
of new pieces and the dispatch

01:00:31.800 --> 01:00:34.240
of finished results,

01:00:34.240 --> 01:00:35.640
and so on.

01:00:36.680 --> 01:00:39.460
Work planning is again associated with

01:00:39.460 --> 01:00:43.180
the name of Taylor, and in fact just

01:00:43.180 --> 01:00:46.220
very often it is planning

01:00:46.220 --> 01:00:48.700
that is often cited as one of

01:00:48.700 --> 01:00:50.840
his most important accomplishments.

01:00:50.880 --> 01:00:52.820
Although, of course, it is pointless

01:00:52.820 --> 01:00:54.160
to argue which of these elements

01:00:54.160 --> 01:00:55.800
seemed more or less important.

01:00:55.880 --> 01:00:57.100
Today we, again, understand very

01:00:57.100 --> 01:00:59.280
well that all of the things we

01:00:59.280 --> 01:01:01.960
are talking about are used in

01:01:01.960 --> 01:01:03.980
the daily activities of any company.

01:01:05.320 --> 01:01:08.700
But in addition to planning these

01:01:08.700 --> 01:01:12.340
objective indicators, Taylor pointed

01:01:12.340 --> 01:01:15.880
out that the social condition

01:01:15.880 --> 01:01:21.420
of workers also plays a role

01:01:21.420 --> 01:01:24.080
in the quality of work.

01:01:24.680 --> 01:01:28.720
If a worker knows that his children

01:01:29.460 --> 01:01:32.120
are looked after while he is working,

01:01:32.120 --> 01:01:34.540
then, accordingly, his thoughts

01:01:34.720 --> 01:01:38.440
will not be scattered to something

01:01:38.440 --> 01:01:40.300
else, and he will be able

01:01:40.300 --> 01:01:42.320
to concentrate all his efforts

01:01:42.320 --> 01:01:43.780
directly on work.

01:01:44.200 --> 01:01:46.760
So, as I said, although Taylor

01:01:46.760 --> 01:01:47.860
did not deal directly

01:01:47.860 --> 01:01:49.280
with the intangible stimulus,

01:01:49.280 --> 01:01:51.440
the ideas were laid out here.

01:01:51.780 --> 01:01:54.020
Taylor emphasized that if we

01:01:54.020 --> 01:01:57.540
engage in collecting socially

01:01:57.540 --> 01:02:00.440
meaningful information about that

01:02:00.440 --> 01:02:03.220
particular worker, about

01:02:03.220 --> 01:02:05.220
that particular social

01:02:05.220 --> 01:02:08.860
group, and promote meaningful

01:02:08.860 --> 01:02:10.940
social needs of the worker,

01:02:11.400 --> 01:02:14.100
then he will perform better.

01:02:15.060 --> 01:02:16.960
Naturally, this idea was later applied

01:02:16.960 --> 01:02:18.800
very widely, especially in the

01:02:18.900 --> 01:02:21.160
next stage of the development

01:02:21.160 --> 01:02:23.300
of organizational research,

01:02:23.300 --> 01:02:24.040
which we will discuss

01:02:24.040 --> 01:02:25.200
a little later.

01:02:26.740 --> 01:02:29.180
In addition to these measures,

01:02:29.320 --> 01:02:32.180
which, in fact, constituted the scientific

01:02:32.180 --> 01:02:36.480
organization of labor, Taylor was one of

01:02:36.480 --> 01:02:39.240
the first to explain scientifically

01:02:39.240 --> 01:02:43.980
such a phenomenon, characteristic of

01:02:43.980 --> 01:02:45.820
industrial production at the end

01:02:45.820 --> 01:02:48.240
of the XIX century, as restrictionism.

01:02:49.260 --> 01:02:52.460
The point is that workers had certain

01:02:52.460 --> 01:02:54.480
standards of production.

01:02:55.200 --> 01:02:56.880
And, naturally, the workers

01:02:56.880 --> 01:02:59.020
were interested in keeping these

01:02:59.020 --> 01:02:59.720
norms low.

01:03:00.320 --> 01:03:03.540
That is, they deliberately

01:03:03.540 --> 01:03:06.300
limited the output of certain

01:03:06.300 --> 01:03:09.720
products, always finding a lot

01:03:09.720 --> 01:03:12.600
of objective reasons.

01:03:13.060 --> 01:03:14.540
Taylor was just pointing out

01:03:15.080 --> 01:03:18.680
that if we provide timing, instruction

01:03:18.800 --> 01:03:20.180
cards, work scheduling,

01:03:21.220 --> 01:03:24.180
then we will have the data

01:03:24.180 --> 01:03:26.380
to say that we can actually increase

01:03:26.380 --> 01:03:27.980
the rate of production here,

01:03:27.980 --> 01:03:30.400
and this increase will

01:03:30.400 --> 01:03:33.540
be absolutely correct and

01:03:33.540 --> 01:03:35.620
not be a further exploitation

01:03:35.620 --> 01:03:36.800
of the survival

01:03:36.800 --> 01:03:37.940
of the runoff

01:03:37.940 --> 01:03:38.940
workers.

01:03:39.500 --> 01:03:43.320
And if we provide social support

01:03:43.320 --> 01:03:45.600
for the worker, as it is now called,

01:03:45.600 --> 01:03:48.240
